  "prompt": "What are the questions asked in interviews?",
  "response": "Interview questions vary widely depending on the role, company, and industry. However, some common categories and examples are frequently used. Here's a breakdown of common interview questions, organized by category:\n\n**I. Behavioral Questions (Past Behavior Predicts Future Behavior):**\n\n*   **Tell me about a time when you failed. What did you learn from it?**\n*   **Describe a situation where you had to overcome a significant obstacle to achieve a goal.**\n*   **Give me an example of a time when you had to work with a difficult person. How did you handle it?**\n*   **Tell me about a time you had to make a decision quickly with limited information.**\n*   **Describe a time you had to adapt to a significant change in the workplace.**\n*   **Tell me about a time you demonstrated leadership skills.** (Even if not a leadership role specifically)\n*   **Give me an example of a time you had to persuade someone to see your point of view.**\n*   **Tell me about a time you had to prioritize multiple tasks with competing deadlines.**\n*   **Describe a time you received negative feedback. How did you react and what did you do with it?**\n*   **Tell me about a time you went above and beyond to help a customer or colleague.**\n*   **Explain a situation where you disagreed with a colleague or supervisor. How did you handle the disagreement?**\n*   **Give me an example of a time you had to learn something new quickly.**\n*   **Tell me about a time when you were part of a successful team.** What was your role?\n\n**To answer behavioral questions effectively, use the STAR method:**\n\n*   **Situation:** Briefly describe the context of the situation.\n*   **Task:** Explain the task or goal you were trying to achieve.\n*   **Action:** Describe the specific actions you took to address the situation.\n*   **Result:** Explain the outcome of your actions and what you learned.\n\n**II. Technical Questions (Specific to the Role):**\n\n*   These questions will be highly specific to the skills and knowledge required for the job.  Examples:\n    *   **Software Engineer:** \"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\" \"Explain the concept of object-oriented programming.\" \"How would you debug a memory leak?\"\n    *   **Marketing Manager:** \"How would you develop a marketing strategy for a new product launch?\" \"Explain your experience with different marketing channels (e.g., SEO, social media, email marketing).\"\n    *   **Accountant:** \"Explain the difference between GAAP and IFRS.\" \"How would you handle a complex reconciliation?\"\n    *   **Data Analyst:** \"Describe your experience with SQL.\" \"How would you handle missing data in a dataset?\"\n    *   **Project Manager:** \"Describe your experience with Agile methodologies.\" \"How do you manage project risks?\"\n*   **Coding challenges:** (For software development roles) You might be asked to write code on a whiteboard or using an online editor.\n*   **Case studies:** (For consulting or business-related roles) You might be given a business problem to solve and asked to present your solution.\n\n**III. General/Situational Questions:**\n\n*   **Tell me about yourself.** (Focus on your relevant experience and skills)\n*   **Why are you interested in this position?** (Show genuine enthusiasm and connect your skills to the job requirements)\n*   **Why are you interested in our company?** (Research the company and understand its mission, values, and culture)\n*   **What are your strengths?** (Choose strengths relevant to the role and provide examples)\n*   **What are your weaknesses?** (Be honest but frame it positively.  Focus on a weakness you're actively working to improve)\n*   **Where do you see yourself in 5 years?** (Show ambition and alignment with the company's goals)\n*   **What are your salary expectations?** (Research industry standards for the role and location)\n*   **What are your hobbies and interests?** (Helps the interviewer get to know you better and assess cultural fit)\n*   **Describe your ideal work environment.**\n*   **What motivates you?**\n*   **How do you handle stress?**\n*   **What are your leadership skills?** (Even if the role is not specifically a leadership role.)\n*   **If you were an animal, what would you be and why?** (Tests creativity and self-awareness - be prepared for unusual questions!)\n*   **How do you define success?**\n\n**IV. Questions About Your Resume:**\n\n*   Be prepared to elaborate on any information on your resume.\n*   **\"Walk me through your resume.\"**\n*   **\"Tell me more about your experience at [Previous Company].\"**\n*   **\"Why did you leave your previous role?\"** (Be positive and professional. Focus on seeking new opportunities)\n*   **\"Explain this gap in your employment history.\"** (Be honest and concise)\n\n**V. Questions for *You* to Ask the Interviewer:**\n\n*   **Always prepare 2-3 thoughtful questions to ask the interviewer.** This shows your interest and engagement.  Examples:\n    *   **\"What are the biggest challenges facing the team right now?\"**\n    *   **\"What opportunities are there for professional development and growth within the company?\"**\n    *   **\"What does a typical day look like in this role?\"**\n    *   **\"What do you enjoy most about working here?\"**\n    *   **\"How does this role contribute to the company's overall goals?\"**\n    *   **\"What are the next steps in the interview process?\"**\n    *   **\"What are the performance expectations for this role during the first six months?\"**\n\n**Key Tips for Preparing for Interviews:**\n\n*   **Research the company and the role:** Understand their mission, values, products/services, and the specific responsibilities of the job.\n*   **Practice answering common interview questions:** Use the STAR method for behavioral questions.\n*   **Prepare examples of your accomplishments:** Quantify your achievements whenever possible (e.g., \"Increased sales by 15%\").\n*   **Dress professionally:** Even for remote interviews.\n*   **Be enthusiastic and positive:** Show genuine interest in the opportunity.\n*   **Listen carefully to the interviewer's questions.**\n*   **Take your time to answer thoughtful.**  It's okay to pause for a moment to collect your thoughts.\n*   **Send a thank-you note (email) to the interviewer within 24 hours:** Reiterate your interest and thank them for their time.\n*   **Practice, practice, practice:** Mock interviews with friends, family, or career counselors can be extremely helpful.\n\nBy preparing for these common types of interview questions, you can increase your confidence and improve your chances of landing the job! Good luck!\n",
